Introduction

This document analyses predator fish biomass from the Kimbe Bay video survey data set.

Data import and wrangling

source("pred_biom_diw.R", local = knitr::knit_global())

Variables:

Modeling predator biomass (response variable) against reef type (fixed effect predictor variable), with site as a random effect:

  1. Biomass (response variable - raw data in grams but diw converts to kg for rest of analysis)
  2. Reef type (predictor variable - fixed effect): Factor with 3 ‘levels’.
  3. Site (nested random effect): 4, nested within reef type, 12 total.
  4. Total biomass of fish (scaling variable): Need to scale the model to account for total fish biomass?? –> Check if this makes a difference

merpredsum has the transect_biomass column in it. Can also run using: source(“pred_biom_eda.R”, local = knitr::knit_global())

- Lots of zeros so perhaps will need a ZI term in the model. - Log hist looks normal so prob will need a distribution on the log scale - Not count data so not really expecting Poisson or neg binom distributions to work best. - As per abundance, predator biomass highest on pinnacles - Exaggerated by large schools of large pelagic/semi-pelagic fishes (in particular S. qenie)

Fit models

Will start with basic GLMM with site as random factor. Definitely not going to be Gaussian, Gamma (zeros), Beta (not 0-1). Will start with Poisson, Neg Binom, ZI and Tweedie. Will introduce offset later on to account for total fish biomass

# Poisson
pred.glmmp <- glmmTMB(Transect_biomass_kg~Reeftype+(1|SiteCode), data=merpredsum_kg, family=genpois())
## Warning in glmmTMB(Transect_biomass_kg ~ Reeftype + (1 | SiteCode), data =
## merpredsum_kg, : non-integer counts in a genpois model
# Negbinom
pred.glmmnb2 <- glmmTMB(Transect_biomass_kg~Reeftype+(1|SiteCode), data=merpredsum_kg, family=nbinom2(link = "log"))  
## Warning in glmmTMB(Transect_biomass_kg ~ Reeftype + (1 | SiteCode), data =
## merpredsum_kg, : non-integer counts in a nbinom2 model
# ZI on nb
pred.glmmzi <- glmmTMB(Transect_biomass_kg~Reeftype+(1|SiteCode), data=merpredsum_kg, family=nbinom2(), ziformula=~1)
## Warning in glmmTMB(Transect_biomass_kg ~ Reeftype + (1 | SiteCode), data =
## merpredsum_kg, : non-integer counts in a nbinom2 model
# Tweedie
pred.glmmt <- glmmTMB(Transect_biomass_kg~Reeftype+(1|SiteCode), data=merpredsum_kg, family=tweedie(link = "log"))

Source code for all models trialled if required (model comparisons etc)

Model tweaking

Now going to add the offset

pred.glmmnboff <- update(pred.glmmnb2, ~ . + offset(log(Transect_Fish_Biomass_kg)))
## Warning in glmmTMB(formula = Transect_biomass_kg ~ Reeftype + (1 | SiteCode) + :
## non-integer counts in a nbinom2 model

Revalidation with AIC

AIC(pred.glmmnboff, pred.glmmnb2)
binned_residuals(pred.glmmnboff)
## Warning: About 82% of the residuals are inside the error bounds (~95% or higher would be good).
  • Offset model better fit

Plots

# emmeans figure
plotresults <- ggplot(results$emmeans, aes(y=response,  x=Reeftype)) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin=lower.CL,  ymax=upper.CL))+
  xlab('Reef type')+
  ylab('Mean (kg biomass per transect)')+
  theme_scientific()

# Contrasts figure
plotcontrasts <- ggplot(results$contrasts, aes(y=estimate,  x=contrast)) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin=lower.CL,  ymax=upper.CL))+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype='dashed')+
  xlab('Contrast')+
  ylab('Contrast estimate (Δ kg biomass per transect)')+
  coord_flip()+
  theme_scientific()

# Plot together
fig <- grid.arrange(plotresults, plotcontrasts, nrow=1)

plot(fig)

# Save
ggsave(fig, filename= '../../output/rfigures/biomass_fig.png', width=10,  height=3, dpi = 400 )
